<s-function-doc>
<s-topics>
<s-topic> dbExecStatement </s-topic>
<s-topic> dbExec </s-topic>
</s-topics>
<s-title>
Execute an SQL statement on a given database connection
</s-title>
<s-description>
Submits and executes an arbitrary SQL statement on a
specific connection.
</s-description>
<s-usage>
<s-old-style-usage>
dbExecStatement(con, statement, ...)
</s-old-style-usage>
<s-old-style-usage>
dbExec(con, statement, ...)
</s-old-style-usage>
</s-usage>
<s-args-required>
<s-arg name= con >
a connection object (i.e., an object that extends 
<s-class>dbConnection</s-class>).
</s-arg>
<s-arg name= statement >
a character vector of length 1 with the SQL statement.
</s-arg>
</s-args-required>
<s-args-optional>
<s-arg name= ... >
database-specific parameters may be specified.
</s-arg>
</s-args-optional>
<s-value>
an object that extends <code>dbResult</code>, in the case of
an SQL statement that produces no output (e.g., <code>INSERT</code>),
or <s-class>dbResultSet</s-class> in the case of a 
<code>SELECT</code>-like statement.
<p>
(NOTE: As of release 0.3.1 we've only implemented
<code>dbResultSet</code> objects for all types of SQL statements.)
</s-value>
<s-side-effects>
The statement is submitted to the server connected through
the connection <code>con.</code>
</s-side-effects>
<s-details>
This function only submits and executes the SQL statement to
the database engine.  It does <em>not</em> extracts any
records:  for that you need to use the function 
<s-function name="fetch.sgm">fetch</s-function>.
</s-details>
